JOHANNESBURG - Mark Lamberti has resigned from the board of power utility Eskom, according to the Department of Public Enterprises. Lamberti, CEO of Imperial, had been the subject of a high court case in which he was accused of gender-based discrimination. READ: EFF joins calls for Lamberti's resignation He referred to former Imperial employee Adila Chowan as a female employment-equity candidate. The North Gauteng High Court found that Chowan had reason to believe she was discriminated against. Public Enterprises Minister Pravin Gordan has commended him for taking the decision to put the interests of Eskom first. Ghordan says Lamberti will also return the fees paid to him by Eskom. Lamberti was appointed to the board in January by President Cyril Ramaphosa. eNCA